    <item>
      <title>Urban Class Structure in Post-Apartheid South Africa at Johannesburg Holocaust &amp; Genocide Centre, South Africa</title>
      <description><![CDATA[<div>  <img src="https://localist-images.azureedge.net/photos/52365492642273/huge/0e571c4fe29df06a773d3500b734a8c24cb66a10.jpg" style="width: 100%;" />  <div style="font-size: 0.9em; color: #555;"><strong>Tue, 31 Mar 2026</strong></div>  <div><p>In honour of Human Rights Month, the Johannesburg Holocaust &amp; Genocide Centre and the Center for African Studies at Howard University invite you to join us for a special presentation by Howard University African Studies Ph.D. candidate DaQuan Lawrence on Urban Class Structure in Post-Apartheid South Africa: Case Studies from Johannesburg and Tshwane.</p>

<p>Johannesburg Holocaust &amp; Genocide Centre in South Africa at 17:45 SAST
<br />RSVP required to <a href="mailto:thulim@jhbholocaust.co.za">thulim@jhbholocaust.co.za</a>.</p>

<p> </p>

<p>Livestream on YouTube at 11:45 EDT
<br /><a href="https://www.youtube.com/c/HUCenterAfrica">https://www.youtube.com/c/HUCenterAfrica</a></p>

<p> </p>

<p>Amid the 32nd anniversary of South Africa’s transition to a democratic and post-apartheid society, Lawrence’s research investigates the class structure in post-apartheid South Africa’s municipalities of Johannesburg and Pretoria. The study seeks to discover how race continues to shape urban class constructions in South Africa, and how the middle class is defined in urban areas.</p>

<p> </p>

<p>DaQuan Lawrence is a Harlem-born human rights activist, educator, journalist, and African Studies Ph.D. candidate at Howard University. His research examines class structure and urban inequality in Africa, developing new global class frameworks grounded in African perspectives.</p>

<p><a href="https://events.howard.edu/event/urban-class-structure-in-post-apartheid-south-africa">View on site</a> | <a href="mailto:?subject=I found an interesting event%3A Urban Class Structure in Post-Apartheid South Africa&amp;body=I found an interesting event you may like%3A%0A%0A%0ADate%3A Mar 31%2C 2026%0A%0ADescription%3A%0AIn honour of Human Rights Month%2C the Johannesburg Holocaust %26 Genocide Centre and the Center for African Studies at Howard University invite you to join us for a special presentation by Howard University African Studies Ph.D. candidate DaQuan Lawrence on Urban Class Structure in Post-Apartheid South Africa%3A Case Studies from Johannesburg and Tshwane.%0A%0A%0AJohannesburg Holocaust %26 Genocide Centre in South Africa at 17%3A45 SAST%0ARSVP required to thulim%40jhbholocaust.co.za.%0A%0A %0A%0ALivestream on YouTube at 11%3A45 EDT%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fc%2FHUCenterAfrica%0A%0A %0A%0AAmid the 32nd anniversary of South Africa%E2%80%99s transition to a democratic and post-apartheid society%2C Lawrence%E2%80%99s research investigates the class structure in post-apartheid South Africa%E2%80%99s municipalities of Johannesburg and Pretoria. The study seeks to discover how race continues to shape urban class constructions in South Africa%2C and how the middle class is defined in urban areas.%0A%0A %0A%0ADaQuan Lawrence is a Harlem-born human rights activist%2C educator%2C journalist%2C and African Studies Ph.D. candidate at Howard University. His research examines class structure and urban inequality in Africa%2C developing new global class frameworks grounded in African perspectives.%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fevents.howard.edu%2Fevent%2Furban-class-structure-in-post-apartheid-south-africa%0A">Email this event</a></p></div></div>]]></description>
